  <main class="landing-main">
    <article class="legal docs">
      <h1><i class="bi bi-journal-text"></i> Documentation</h1>
      <p class="section-lead">
        Short and to the point: what you need to know to use web-obsidian effectively.
      </p>

      <nav class="docs-toc" aria-label="Contents">
        <a href="#what">What web-obsidian is</a>
        <a href="#sync">Changes are not real-time</a>
        <a href="#backup">Backing up your vault</a>
        <a href="#trash">Deleting files (trash)</a>
        <a href="#twofa">Two-factor authentication</a>
        <a href="#encryption">At-rest encryption</a>
        <a href="#password">No password reset</a>
        <a href="#weblinks">Web links</a>
        <a href="#files">Supported files</a>
        <a href="#architecture">Architecture</a>
      </nav>

      <section class="legal-section" id="what">
        <h2>What web-obsidian is (and is not)</h2>
        <p>
          web-obsidian is an independent open-source project. It is <strong>not</strong> the
          original Obsidian (obsidian.md), not affiliated with it, and not a competing product.
          The name only describes the idea: an Obsidian-style markdown vault you reach from a
          web browser.
        </p>
        <p>
          The original Obsidian is a desktop/mobile app that stores notes locally on each
          device and uses a separate sync service to keep devices in step. web-obsidian works
          the other way around: your vault lives on the server and you simply log in.
        </p>
        <p>
          Why does that matter? In many organisations &mdash; companies, agencies, enterprise
          laptops &mdash; you are not allowed to install private sync clients or arbitrary apps.
          A local-vault-plus-sync setup is then impossible. A web browser, however, is almost
          always available, so your knowledge vault stays reachable. On top of that:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Nothing to install &mdash; no app, no sync client.</li>
          <li>No local storage used on your phone or PC.</li>
          <li>No encrypted backups for you to manage &mdash; the server handles encryption.</li>
          <li>Deliberately simple: just what you need day to day, not a feature maze.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="docs-quote">
          The human brain is made for having ideas, not for holding them. web-obsidian is your
          second brain.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="sync">
        <h2>Changes are not real-time</h2>
        <p>
          If you edit on device A, then look at device B, you must <strong>reload the browser
          on device B</strong> to see the change. Updates are not pushed live.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is a direct consequence of at-rest encryption: content is stored encrypted and
          only decrypted when you request it, so each device sees the latest version the next
          time it loads a note &mdash; not the instant it changes elsewhere.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="backup">
        <h2>Backing up your vault</h2>
        <p>
          Click <strong>Export</strong> in the sidebar. Your entire vault is downloaded as a
          single <code>.zip</code> file with the original folder structure.
        </p>
        <p>
          The export is <strong>decrypted</strong> on the way out, so the zip is a portable,
          platform-independent backup you can open anywhere or re-import later.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="trash">
        <h2>Deleting files (trash &amp; recovery window)</h2>
        <p>
          When you delete a file or folder it is <strong>not erased right away</strong>. It is
          moved to a hidden, per-account trash so an accidental deletion can be recovered. While
          an item sits in the trash it is hidden from your file tree, but it still
          <strong>counts toward your storage quota</strong> until it is permanently removed.
        </p>
        <p>
          A daily clean-up job permanently removes items that have been in the trash longer than
          a fixed <strong>retention window</strong> &mdash; <strong>7 days by default</strong>.
          The job runs once a day, so the retention setting controls <em>how long an item stays
          recoverable</em>, not how often the clean-up runs. After the window passes the item is
          gone for good and cannot be restored.
        </p>
        <p>
          Self-hosting? The window is configurable with the
          <code>TRASH_RETENTION_DAYS</code> environment variable (set it to <code>0</code> to
          disable the trash entirely so deletions are immediate).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="twofa">
        <h2>Two-factor authentication (2FA / TOTP)</h2>
        <p>
          TOTP (Time-based One-Time Password) is the 6-digit code that rotates every 30 seconds
          in an authenticator app. On sign-in you provide your password <em>and</em> the current
          code, so a stolen password alone is not enough to reach your vault.
        </p>
        <p>
          2FA is <strong>required</strong>, not optional, because your notes are sensitive and a
          single secret is too weak to protect them. Set it up once during registration by
          scanning the QR code.
        </p>
        <p>
          Got a new phone or switched authenticator app? You can <strong>change (reset) your
          authenticator</strong> any time from the dashboard under
          <em>Account &rarr; Security &rarr; Reset authenticator (2FA)</em>. For your safety the
          reset requires your current password <em>and</em> a code from your existing
          authenticator; you then scan a fresh QR code and confirm a code from the new device to
          switch over. The old code stops working as soon as the new one is confirmed.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="encryption">
        <h2>At-rest encryption (and why not end-to-end)</h2>
        <p>
          Every file &mdash; notes, drawings, attachments, documents &mdash; is encrypted with
          AES-256-GCM on the server before it is written to disk or object storage. The stored
          data is unreadable on its own.
        </p>
        <p>
          We chose <strong>at-rest</strong> encryption over end-to-end (E2E) on purpose. True E2E
          would require the decryption key to live only in your browser. That makes server-side
          rendering, full-text search and the password-change flow impossible without shipping
          all your data to the client, and &mdash; critically &mdash; if you lost that key,
          every note would be permanently unrecoverable. At-rest encryption protects the stored
          data while keeping the product simple and usable.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="password">
        <h2>There is a password change &mdash; but no password reset</h2>
        <p>
          You can change your password any time from the dashboard (current password + a 2FA
          code are required). You can likewise <strong>change your authenticator</strong> while
          you still have access (see <a href="#twofa">Two-factor authentication</a> above).
          There is, however, <strong>no &ldquo;forgot password&rdquo; reset</strong>
          and no recovery for a lost TOTP secret once you can no longer sign in.
        </p>
        <p>
          So: <strong>never lose your password or your TOTP secret.</strong> We strongly
          recommend a password manager &mdash; for example
          <a href="https://bitwarden.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Bitwarden</a>
          &mdash; to store your password and to hold your 2FA (Bitwarden can generate the TOTP
          codes for you).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="weblinks">
        <h2>Web links (save a link once, open it safely forever)</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>Web links</strong> manager lets you keep your important links inside your
          vault &mdash; with a name, category and description &mdash; instead of scattering them
          across browser bookmarks. Open the manager from the toolbar, add a link or import a CSV
          (the Linky export format is supported), and search across everything you saved.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The idea.</strong> Your bookmarks normally live inside one browser on one
          device. Reinstall the browser, switch machines, or log in from a locked-down work
          computer and they are gone. Web links live in your encrypted vault, so they travel with
          your account: save a link once and reach it from anywhere you can open web-obsidian.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Why it is safer.</strong> The risky moment with any link is the
          <em>first</em> time &mdash; that is when you judge whether a URL really points where it
          claims. Vet a link once, store the exact address, and from then on you always open
          <em>that</em> verified URL. You are no longer re-reading a link someone pasted into an
          email or chat, where the visible text can hide a different, manipulated destination.
          The stored URL is encrypted at rest like the rest of your vault.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Independent of the browser.</strong> Because the links are kept server-side in
          your vault rather than in a browser profile, they are not tied to any one browser,
          extension or sync account. Nothing to install, nothing to export when you move devices
          &mdash; just log in and your trusted links are there.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="files">
        <h2>Supported files</h2>
        <p>
          Beyond markdown and Excalidraw, you can browse a wide range of files like in a code
          editor &mdash; <code>.py</code>, <code>.ts</code>, <code>.js</code>, <code>.json</code>,
          <code>.yaml</code>, <code>.toml</code>, <code>.sh</code>, <code>.html</code>,
          <code>.css</code>, <code>.conf</code> and many more &mdash; with syntax highlighting.
          Word (<code>.docx</code>), Excel (<code>.xlsx</code>/<code>.xls</code>) and
          OpenDocument (<code>.odt</code>/<code>.ods</code>) files render read-only in the
          browser. All of them are encrypted at rest just like your notes.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="legal-section" id="architecture">
        <h2>Architecture (for technical users)</h2>
        <img class="docs-architecture" src="/public/web-obsidian-architecture.png"
             alt="web-obsidian architecture diagram" loading="lazy" />
        <ul>
          <li><strong>HTTP-only auth token</strong> &mdash; the session cookie is HTTP-only, so it cannot be read or manipulated by XSS JavaScript attacks.</li>
          <li><strong>NestJS backend</strong> with server-side rendered EJS views.</li>
          <li><strong>Cloudflare Zero Trust tunnel</strong> into the <code>fabo011-cloud.de</code> private network.</li>
          <li><strong>Docker Swarm</strong> for container orchestration.</li>
          <li><strong>PostgreSQL</strong> database for user data - encrypted.</li>
          <li><strong>Node.js crypto</strong> for at-rest encryption &mdash; all files are encrypted (AES-256-GCM).</li>
          <li><strong>S3-compatible storage</strong> for the encrypted vault contents.</li>
          <li><strong>Encrypted backups</strong> to MEGA object storage.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>

  <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>
</html>
